JAMF Protect Add-on for Splunk
Version 1.5.1

Documentation

Overview

	The Jamf Protect Add-on for Splunk will accelerate organizational time-to-value with onboarding their Jamf Protect data into Splunk.  Data has been normalized to the Alerts, Authentication, and Malware Data Models.  Additional field normalization has been completed for fields relevant to the Change and Endpoint Data Models as well, but tags and event types have not been added to this release for those event types.

	CIM data model normalization has been performed to align the Jamf Protect events with Malware and Alerts data models where appropriate.

Installation / Configuration
	For the latest installation and configuration information, please see our website at https://[ Need to get a link up on our website ]


	1. This add-on contains Index time and Search time operations. Therefore it should be installed appropriately on the Search and Index tier. If you are using a Heavy Forwarder to process the data before sending to the indexers, then you should install the TA on the HF and it will not be necessary on the indexers.
	2. Add-on expects an initial sourcetype of "jamf:protect:alerts".  Please configure your inputs accordingly or this add-on will not do anything. This is essential for the index time operations.
	3a. (Splunk Cloud) 
		For existing data compatibility, you will need to make a search time rename for the existing sourcetype.  To do this, go to Settings > Sourcetype > the sourcetype your Jamf Protect is currently set to > New Setting. Add a line for "rename" = "Jamf:protect:alerts". Save.  This will rename the old source type at search time and allow splunk to utilize the search time settings from this TA.
	3b. (Splunk On Premise) 
		For existing data compatibility, copy the top line from default/props.conf to local/props.conf and set the appropriate original sourcetype. This will not change your data, it will only allow you to use the search time extractions from this app with your existing sourcetype.  PLEASE make sure that your new data is using the sourcetype of "jamf:protect:alerts" for best compatibilitity with the addon.
		Example:
		###
		[EXISTING-SOURCETYPE]
		rename = jamf:protect:alerts
	4a. (Splunk Cloud) Update the base eventtype by going to Settings > Event Types > jamf_protect. Edit the event type and update the index to the correct value.
	4b. (Splunk on Premise) Update the base eventtype by copying the setting below from default/eventtypes.conf to local/eventtypes.conf. Then replace index=* with the index your jamf:protect data is in.
		[jamf_protect]
		search = index=* sourcetype="jamf:protect:alerts"
	5. Ensure the data models are accelerated and have been updated to support the indexes for Jamf Protect data.  This addon is designed to support the Alerts and Malware data models.
	6a. Our default configuration considers the following mappings
		Known Malware/Threats = Map to Malware Datamodel (GPThreatMatchExecEvent & GPPreventedExecutionEvent)
		Alerts with severity > informational = Map to Alerts
		Alerts with unknown or informational severity = Not mapped
	6b. Suspicious threats come from GPGateKeeperEvent and GPFSEvent types. We have mapped these to Alerts. If you wish to map them to Malware, copy the default/tags.conf to local/tags.conf and disable alert tag and enable attack and malware tags.
Support

	There is no support expressed or implied with this release. If you required additional support with this add-on, please contact the Jamf Sales organization.

Documentation
	For information regarding getting your data in to Splunk, please see the Jamf Protect documentation on Data Management > Splunk Integration, https://docs.jamf.com/jamf-protect/documentation/Splunk_Integration.html
